## Context

During ticket 0243's Sample 3 arbitration (PR #1053), the author flagged
"z-score" as undefined jargon in Appendix A.4 and asked for a gloss
("standard deviations from the mean"). A roar-step-3 sweep for the same
anti-pattern elsewhere in the appendix found two more instances, same
class, not yet fixed:

- **"silhouette"** (@fig scores, A.3, three uses: "silhouette scores stay
  near zero at every candidate number of groups, at 0.025 for six", plus
  two more) — never defined. A general HET/STS reader has no way to know
  what the metric measures or what "near zero" means for it.
- **"adjusted Rand index"** (A.3, three uses: 0.59, 0.98, 0.06 to 0.22
  across different comparisons) — never defined. Same problem: no reader
  cue for what the metric is or how to read the range (0 = chance
  agreement, 1 = identical partitions).

## Relevant files

- `deliverables/manuscript/manuscript.qmd` — Appendix A.3, "What is
  embedded, and how the texts are grouped" section (search "silhouette",
  "Rand index")

## Actions

1. Author decides the gloss wording for each term (matching the "z-score"
   precedent: short parenthetical, plain language, no dash — see PR #1053
   commit message for the pattern).
2. Apply via the same author-arbitrated, primary-source-verified process
   used throughout ticket 0243 (no autonomous rewrite of manuscript prose).

## Test

- No red step — this is prose, not code. Guard: `make check-fast` +
  `tests/test_manuscript_prose.py` stay green; no factual/numerical/citation
  change; em-dash ratchet does not rise.

